In addition to confirming that at least some dinosaurs were feathered, a theory now widely accepted, it also provides specific data that fossils usually do not offer, such as their color and their three-dimensional structure.
According to specialists, this animal has brown plumage on the upper part and a pale or carotenoid tone on the underside.
Likewise, the discovery allows for a better understanding of the evolution of bird feathers.
Since the plumage of dinosaurs does not have a well-developed central shaft, called a rachis, but does present other features of feathers (bristles and barbs), researchers have concluded that it is likely that the rachis is the result of a later evolutionary development of these other characteristics.
The structure of the plumage suggests that its function was not related to flight, but rather that it was used to regulate temperature or as an indicator of it. Researchers argue that, although it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample analyzed shows features of adult plumage and not of a chick.
The experts' observations were that, even though it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample illustrates more the plumage of an adult than that of a chick.
